149 /**
150 CostingReceiver contains the main join planning logic, selecting access paths
151 based on cost. It receives subplans from DPhyp (see enumerate_subgraph.h),
152 assigns them costs based on a cost model, and keeps the ones that are
153 cheapest. In the end, this means it will be left with a root access path that
154 gives the lowest total cost for joining the tables in the query block, ie.,
155 without ORDER BY etc.
156
157 Currently, besides the expected number of produced rows (which is the same no
158 matter how we access the table) we keep only a single value per subplan
159 (total cost), and thus also only a single best access path. In the future,
160 we will have more dimensions to worry about, such as initial cost versus total
161 cost (relevant for LIMIT), ordering properties, and so on. At that point,
162 there is not necessarily a single “best” access path anymore, and we will need
163 to keep multiple ones around, and test all of them as candidates when building
164 larger subplans.
165 */
166 class CostingReceiver {
167 public:

262 /**
263 Besides the access paths for a set of nodes (see m_access_paths),
264 AccessPathSet contains information that is common between all access
265 paths for that set. One would believe num_output_rows would be such
266 a member (a set of tables should produce the same number of output
267 rows no matter the join order), but due to parameterized paths,
268 different access paths could have different outputs. delayed_predicates
269 is another, but currently, it's already efficiently hidden space-wise
270 due to the use of a union.
271 */
272 struct AccessPathSet {
273 Prealloced_array<AccessPath *, 4> paths;
274 FunctionalDependencySet active_functional_dependencies{0};
275
276 // Once-interesting orderings that we don't care about anymore,
277 // e.g. because they were interesting for a semijoin but that semijoin
278 // is now done (with or without using the ordering). This reduces
279 // the number of access paths we have to keep in play, since they are
280 // de-facto equivalent.
281 //
282 // Note that if orderings were merged, this could falsely prune out
283 // orderings that we would actually need, but as long as all of the
284 // relevant ones are semijoin orderings (which are never identical,
285 // and never merged with the relevant-at-end orderings), this
286 // should not happen.
287 OrderingSet obsolete_orderings{0};
288 };
289
290 /**
291 For each subset of tables that are connected in the join hypergraph,
292 keeps the current best access paths for producing said subset.
293 There can be several that are best in different ways; see comments
294 on ProposeAccessPath().
295
296 Also used for communicating connectivity information back to DPhyp
297 (in HasSeen()); if there's an entry here, that subset will induce
298 a connected subgraph of the join hypergraph.
299 */
300 std::unordered_map<NodeMap, AccessPathSet> m_access_paths;
301
302 /**
303 How many subgraph pairs we've seen so far. Used to give up
304 if we end up allocating too many resources (prompting us to
305 create a simpler join graph and try again).
306 */
307 int m_num_seen_subgraph_pairs = 0;
308
309 /// The graph we are running over.
310 const JoinHypergraph *m_graph;
311
312 /// Whether we have applied clamping due to a multi-column EQ_REF at any
313 /// point. There is a known issue (see bug #33550360) where this can cause
314 /// row count estimates to be inconsistent between different access paths.
315 /// Obviously, we should fix this bug by adjusting the selectivities
316 /// (and we do for single-column indexes), but for multipart indexes,
317 /// this is nontrivial. See the bug for details on some ideas, but the
318 /// gist of it is that we probably will want a linear program to adjust
319 /// multi-selectivities so that they are consistent, and not above 1/N
320 /// (for N-row tables) if there are unique indexes on them.
321 ///
322 /// The only reason why we collect this information, like
323 /// JoinHypergraph::has_reordered_left_joins, is to be able to assert
324 /// on inconsistent row counts between APs, excluding this (known) issue.
325 bool has_clamped_multipart_eq_ref = false;
326
327 /// Keeps track of interesting orderings in this query block.
328 /// See LogicalOrderings for more information.
329 const LogicalOrderings *m_orderings;
330
331 /// List of all orderings that are candidates for sort-ahead
332 /// (because they are, or may eventually become, an interesting ordering).
333 const Mem_root_array<SortAheadOrdering> *m_sort_ahead_orderings;
334
335 /// List of all indexes that are active and that we can apply in this query.
336 /// Indexes can be useful in several ways: We can use them for ref access,
337 /// for index-only scans, or to get interesting orderings.
338 const Mem_root_array<ActiveIndexInfo> *m_active_indexes;
339
340 /// List of all active full-text indexes that we can apply in this query.
341 const Mem_root_array<FullTextIndexInfo> *m_fulltext_searches;
342
343 /// A map of tables that are referenced by a MATCH function (those tables that
344 /// have TABLE_LIST::is_fulltext_searched() == true). It is used for
345 /// preventing hash joins involving tables that are full-text searched.
346 NodeMap m_fulltext_tables = 0;
347
348 /// The set of WHERE predicates which are on a form that can be satisfied by a
349 /// full-text index scan. This includes calls to MATCH with no comparison
350 /// operator, and predicates on the form MATCH > const or MATCH >= const
351 /// (where const must be high enough to make the comparison return false for
352 /// documents with zero score).
353 uint64_t m_sargable_fulltext_predicates = 0;
354
355 /// The target tables of an UPDATE or DELETE statement.
356 NodeMap m_update_delete_target_nodes = 0;
357
358 /// The set of tables that are candidates for immediate update or delete.
359 /// Immediate update/delete means that the rows from the table are deleted
360 /// while reading the rows from the topmost iterator. (As opposed to buffered
361 /// update/delete, where the row IDs are stored in temporary tables, and only
362 /// updated or deleted after the topmost iterator has been read to the end.)
363 /// The candidates are those target tables that are only referenced once in
364 /// the query. The requirement for immediate deletion is that the deleted row
365 /// will not have to be read again later. Currently, at most one of the
366 /// candidate tables is chosen, and it is always the outermost table in the
367 /// join tree.
368 NodeMap m_immediate_update_delete_candidates = 0;
369
370 /// Whether we will be needing row IDs from our tables, typically for
371 /// a later sort. If this happens, derived tables cannot use streaming,
372 /// but need an actual materialization, since filesort expects to be
373 /// able to go back and ask for a given row. (This is different from
374 /// when we need row IDs for weedout, which doesn't preclude streaming.
375 /// The hypergraph optimizer does not use weedout.)
376 bool m_need_rowid;
377
378 /// The flags declared by the secondary engine. In particular, it describes
379 /// what kind of access path types should not be created.
380 SecondaryEngineFlags m_engine_flags;
381
382 /// The maximum number of pairs of subgraphs we are willing to accept,
383 /// or -1 if no limit. If this limit gets hit, we stop traversing the graph
384 /// and return an error; the caller will then have to modify the hypergraph
385 /// (see GraphSimplifier) to make for a graph with fewer options, so that
386 /// planning time will come under an acceptable limit.
387 int m_subgraph_pair_limit;
388
389 /// Pointer to a function that modifies the cost estimates of an access path
390 /// for execution in a secondary storage engine, or nullptr otherwise.
391 secondary_engine_modify_access_path_cost_t m_secondary_engine_cost_hook;
392
393 /// If not nullptr, we store human-readable optimizer trace information here.
394 string *m_trace;
395
396 /// A map of tables that can never be on the right side of any join,
397 /// ie., they have to be leftmost in the tree. This only affects recursive
398 /// table references (ie., when WITH RECURSIVE is in use); they work by
399 /// continuously tailing new records, which wouldn't work if we were to
400 /// scan them multiple times or put them in a hash table. Naturally,
401 /// there must be zero or one bit here; the common case is zero.
402 NodeMap forced_leftmost_table = 0;
403
404 /// A special MEM_ROOT for allocating OverflowBitsets that we might end up
405 /// discarding, ie. for AccessPaths that do not yet live in m_access_paths.
406 /// For any AccessPath that is to have a permanent life (ie., not be
407 /// immediately discarded as inferior), the OverflowBitset _must_ be taken
408 /// out of this MEM_ROOT and onto the regular one, as it is cleared often.
409 /// (This significantly reduces the amount of memory used in situations
410 /// where lots of AccessPaths are produced and discarded. Of course,
411 /// it only matters for queries with >= 64 predicates.)
412 ///
413 /// The copying is using CommitBitsetsToHeap(). ProposeAccessPath() will
414 /// automatically call CommitBitsetsToHeap() for accepted access paths,
415 /// but it will not call it on any of their children. Thus, if you've
416 /// added more than one AccessPath in the chain (e.g. if you add a join,
417 /// then a sort of that join, and then propose the sort), you will need
418 /// to make sure there are no stray bitsets left on this MEM_ROOT.
419 ///
420 /// Because this can be a source of subtle bugs, you should be conservative
421 /// about what bitsets you put here; really, only the ones you could be
422 /// allocating many of (like joins) should be candidates.
423 MEM_ROOT m_overflow_bitset_mem_root;
424
425 /// A special MEM_ROOT for temporary data for the range optimizer.
426 /// It can be discarded immediately after we've decided on the range scans
427 /// for a given table (but we reuse its memory as long as there are more
428 /// tables left to scan).
429 MEM_ROOT m_range_optimizer_mem_root;

962 /**
963 Based on estimates for all the different range scans (which cover different
964 but potentially overlapping combinations of predicates), try to find an
965 estimate for the number of rows scanning the given table, with all predicates
966 applied.
967
968 The #1 priority here is to get a single estimate for all (non-parameterized)
969 scans over this table (including non-range scans), that we can reuse for all
970 access paths. This makes sure they are fairly compared on cost (and ordering)
971 alone; different estimates would be nonsensical, and cause those where we
972 happen to have lower estimates to get preferred as they are joined higher up
973 in the tree. Obviously, however, it is also attractive to get an estimate that
974 is as good as possible. We only really care about the total selectivity of all
975 predicates; we don't care to adjust each individual selectivity.
976
977 [Mar07] describes an unbiased estimator that is exactly what we want,
978 and [Hav20] demonstrates an efficient calculation method (up to about 20–25
979 possible predicates) of this estimator. Long-term, implementing this would be
980 our best choice. However, the implementation is not entirely trivial:
981
982 - If the selectivity estimates are not consistent (e.g. S(a AND b) <
983 S(a)S(b)), the algorithm will fail to converge. Extra steps are needed to
984 correct for this.
985 - The efficient algorithm (in [Hav20]) requires a linear algebra library
986 (for performant matrix multiplication and Cholesky decomposition).
987 - If we have a _lot_ of estimates, even the efficient algorithm fails to
988 converge in time (just the answers require 2^n space), and we would need
989 additional logic to partition the problem.
990
991 Thus, for the time being, we use an ad-hoc algorithm instead. The estimate
992 will not be as good, but it will hopefully be on the pessimistic side
993 (overestimating the number of rows). It goes as follows:
994
995 1. Pick the most-covering index (ie., the range scan that applies
996 the most number of predicates) that does not cover any predicates we've
997 already accounted for. If there are multiple ones, choose the least
998 selective.
999 2. Multiply in its selectivity, and mark all the predicates it covers
1000 as accounted for. Repeat #1 and #2 for as long as possible.
1001 3. For any remaining predicates, multiply by their existing estimate
1002 (ie., the one not coming from the range optimizer).
1003
1004 The hope is that in #1, we will usually prefer using selectivity information
1005 from indexes with more keyparts; e.g., it's better to use an index on (a,b)
1006 than on (a) alone, since it will take into account the correlation between
1007 predicates on a and predicates on b.
1008
1009
1010 [Mar07]: Markl et al: “Consistent Selectivity Estimation Via Maximum Entropy”
1011 [Hav20]: Havenstein et al: “Fast Entropy Maximization for Selectivity
1012 Estimation of Conjunctive Predicates on CPUs and GPUs”
1013 */

1094 /**
1095 From a collection of index scans, find the single cheapest one and generate an
1096 AccessPath for it. This is similar to CollectPossibleRangeScans(), except that
1097 this is for index merge, where we don't want to enumerate all possibilities;
1098 since we don't care about the ordering of the index (we're going to sort all
1099 of the rows to deduplicate them anyway), cost is the only interesting metric,
1100 so we only need to pick out and collect ranges for one of them.
1101 (This isn't strictly true; sometimes, it can be attractive to choose a
1102 clustered primary key, so we prefer one if we allow them. See the code about
1103 is_preferred_cpk below, and the comment on the caller. Also, see about
1104 exactness below.)

1107 (just check is_ror_scan instead of is_imerge_scan).

1204 /**
1205 Represents a candidate index merge, ie. an OR expression of several
1206 range scans across different indexes (that can be reconciled by doing
1207 deduplication by sorting on row IDs).
1208
1209 Each predicate (in our usual sense of “part of a top-level AND conjunction in
1210 WHERE”) can give rise to multiple index merges (if there are AND conjunctions
1211 within ORs), but one index merge arises from exactly one predicate.
1212 This is not an inherent limitation, but it is how tree_and() does it;
1213 if it takes two SEL_TREEs with index merges, it just combines their candidates
1214 wholesale; each will deal with one predicate, and the other one would just
1215 have to be applied as a filter.
1216
1217 This is obviously suboptimal, as there are many cases where we could do
1218 better. Imagine something like (a = 3 OR b > 3) AND b <= 5, with separate
1219 indexes on a and b; obviously, we could have applied this as a single index
1220 merge between two range scans: (a = 3 AND b <= 5) OR (b > 3 AND b <= 5). But
1221 this is probably not a priority for us, so we follow the range optimizer's
1222 lead here and record each index merge as covering a separate, single
1223 predicate.
1224 */
1225 struct PossibleIndexMerge {
1226 // The index merge itself (a list of range optimizer trees,
1227 // implicitly ORed together).
1228 SEL_IMERGE *imerge;
1229
1230 // Which WHERE predicate it came from.
1231 size_t pred_idx;
1232
1233 // If true, the index merge does not faithfully represent the entire
1234 // predicate (it could return more rows), and needs to be re-checked
1235 // with a filter.
1236 bool inexact;
1237 };

1693 // Specifies a mapping in a TABLE_REF between an index keypart and a condition,

2284 // Checks if a given predicate can be subsumed by a full-text index. It can
2285 // be subsumed if it returns TRUE for all documents returned by the full-text
2286 // index, and FALSE for all other documents. Since a full-text index scan
2287 // returns the documents with a positive score, predicates that are either a
2288 // standalone call to MATCH, a comparison of MATCH > 0, or a comparison of
2289 // 0 < MATCH, are considered subsumable.

2337 // Assuming that we have chosen a full-text index scan on the given predicate,
2338 // can we pass the LIMIT of the query block as a hint to the storage engine?
2339 //
2340 // We can do this if we know that the number of rows seen before the LIMIT
2341 // clause is processed, is the same number of rows as returned by the index
2342 // scan. This is the case when:

2718 /**
2719 Decide whether joining the two given paths would create a disallowed
2720 parameterized path. Parameterized paths are disallowed if they delay
2721 joining in their parameterizations without reason (ie., they could
2722 join in a parameterization right away, but don't). This is a trick
2723 borrowed from Postgres, which essentially forces inner-join ref-lookup
2724 plans to be left-deep (since such plans never gain anything from being
2725 bushy), reducing the search space significantly without compromising
2726 plan quality.

3152 // Of all delayed predicates, see which ones we can apply now, and which
3153 // ones that need to be delayed further.
3154 1509 void CostingReceiver::ApplyDelayedPredicatesAfterJoin(
3155 NodeMap left, NodeMap right, const AccessPath *left_path,
3156 const AccessPath *right_path, int join_predicate_first,
3157 int join_predicate_last, bool materialize_subqueries, AccessPath *join_path,
3158 FunctionalDependencySet *new_fd_set) {
3159 // We build up a new FD set each time; it should be the same for the same
3160 // left/right pair, so it is somewhat redundant, but it allows us to verify
3161 // that property through the assert in ProposeAccessPathWithOrderings().
3162 1509 new_fd_set->reset();
3163
3164 // Keep track of which multiple equalities we have created predicates for
3165 // so far. We use this to avoid applying redundant predicates, ie. predicates
3166 // that have already been checked. (This is not only to avoid unneeded work,
3167 // but to avoid double-counting the selectivity.)
3168 //
3169 // Avoiding redundant predicates for a multi-equality is equivalent to never
3170 // applying those that would cause loops in the subgraph induced by the tables
3171 // involved in the multi-equality. (In other words, we are building spanning
3172 // trees in the induced subgraph.) In general, every time we connect two
3173 // subgraphs, we must apply every relevant multi-equality exactly once,
3174 // and ignore the others. (This is vaguely reminiscent of Kruskal's algorithm
3175 // for constructing minimum spanning trees.)
3176 //
3177 // DPhyp only ever connects subgraphs that are not already connected
3178 // (ie., it already constructs spanning trees), so we know that the join
3179 // conditions applied earlier are never redundant wrt. the rest of the graph.
3180 // Thus, we only need to test the delayed predicates below; they _may_ contain
3181 // a multiple equality we haven't already applied, but they may also be new,
3182 // e.g. in this graph:
3183 //
3184 // b
3185 // /|\ .
3186 // a | d
3187 // \|/
3188 // c
3189 //
3190 // If we have a multiple equality over {b,c,d}, and connect a-b and then a-c,
3191 // the edge b-c will come into play and contain a multi-equality that was not
3192 // applied before. We will need to apply that multi-equality (we will
3193 // only get one of d-b and d-c). However, if we instead connected d-b
3194 // and d-c, the edge b-c will now be redundant and must be ignored
3195 // (except for functional dependencies). We simply track which ones have been
3196 // applied this iteration by keeping a bitmap of them.
3197 1509 uint64_t multiple_equality_bitmap = 0;
3198

3299 /**
3300 Check if we're about to apply a join condition that would be redundant
3301 with regards to an already-applied sargable predicate, ie., whether our
3302 join condition and the sargable predicate applies the same multiple equality.
3303 E.g. if we try to join {t1,t2} and {t3} along t1=t3, but the access path
3304 for t3 already has applied the join condition t2=t3, and these are from the
3305 same multiple equality, return true.
3306
3307 Even though this is totally _legal_, having such a situation is bad, because
3308
3309 a) It double-counts the selectivity, causing the overall row estimate
3310 to become too low.
3311 b) It causes unneeded work by adding a redundant filter.
3312
3313 b) would normally cause the path to be pruned out due to cost, except that
3314 the artificially low row count due to a) could make the path attractive as a
3315 subplan of a larger join. Thus, we simply reject these joins; we'll see a
3316 different alternative for this join at some point that is not redundant
3317 (e.g., in the given example, we'd see the t2=t3 join).
3318 */
3319 1581 bool CostingReceiver::RedundantThroughSargable(
3320 OverflowBitset redundant_against_sargable_predicates,
3321 const AccessPath *left_path, const AccessPath *right_path, NodeMap left,
3322 NodeMap right) {
3323 // For a join condition to be redundant against an already applied sargable
3324 // predicate, the applied predicate must somehow connect the left side and the
3325 // right side. This means either:
3326 //
3327 // - One of the paths must be parameterized on at least one of the tables in
3328 // the other path. In the example above, because t2=t3 is applied on the {t3}
3329 // path, and t2 is not included in the path, the {t3} path is parameterized on
3330 // t2. (It is only necessary to check if right_path is parameterized on
3331 // left_path, since parameterization is always resolved by nested-loop joining
3332 // in the parameter tables from the outer/left side into the parameterized
3333 // path on the inner/right side.)
3334 //
3335 // - Or both paths are parameterized on some common table that is not part of
3336 // either path. Say if {t1,t2} has sargable t1=t4 and {t3} has sargable t3=t4,
3337 // then both paths are parameterized on t4, and joining {t1,t2} with {t3}
3338 // along t1=t3 is redundant, given all three predicates (t1=t4, t3=t4, t1=t3)
3339 // are from the same multiple equality.
3340 //
3341 // If the parameterization is not like that, we don't need to check any
3342 // further.

4041 /**
4042 Propose the given access path as an alternative to the existing access paths
4043 for the same task (assuming any exist at all), and hold a “tournament” to find
4044 whether it is better than the others. Only the best alternatives are kept,
4045 as defined by CompareAccessPaths(); a given access path is kept only if
4046 it is not dominated by any other path in the group (ie., the Pareto frontier
4047 is computed). This means that the following are all possible outcomes of the
4048 tournament:
4049
4050 - The path is discarded, without ever being inserted in the list
4051 (dominated by at least one existing entry).
4052 - The path is inserted as a new alternative in the list (dominates none
4053 but it also not dominated by any -- or the list was empty), leaving it with
4054 N+1 entries.
4055 - The path is inserted as a new alternative in the list, but replaces one
4056 or more entries (dominates them).
4057 - The path replaces all existing alternatives, and becomes the sole entry
4058 in the list.
4059
4060 “description_for_trace” is a short description of the inserted path
4061 to distinguish it in optimizer trace, if active. For instance, one might
4062 write “hash join” when proposing a hash join access path. It may be
4063 the empty string.
4064
4065 If the access path is discarded, returns nullptr. Otherwise returns
4066 a pointer to where it was inserted. (This is useful if you need to
4067 call CommitBitsetsToHeap() on any of its children, or otherwise do
4068 work only for access paths that were kept.)
4069 */
4070 2507 AccessPath *CostingReceiver::ProposeAccessPath(
4071 AccessPath *path, Prealloced_array<AccessPath *, 4> *existing_paths,
4072 OrderingSet obsolete_orderings, const char *description_for_trace) const {

4453 /**
4454 Goes through an item tree and collects all the sub-items that should be
4455 materialized if full-text search is used in combination with sort-based
4456 aggregation.
4457
4458 This means all expressions in the SELECT list, GROUP BY clause, ORDER BY
4459 clause and HAVING clause that are possible to evaluate before aggregation.
4460
4461 The reason why this materialization is needed, is that
4462 Item_func_match::val_real() can only be evaluated if the underlying scan is
4463 positioned on the row for which the full-text search score is to be retrieved.
4464 In the sort-based aggregation performed by AggregateIterator, the rows are
4465 returned with the underlying scan positioned on some other row (typically one
4466 in the next group). Even though AggregateIterator restores the contents of the
4467 record buffers to what they had when the scan was positioned on that row, it
4468 is not enough; the handler needs to be repositioned to make Item_func_match
4469 give the correct result. To avoid this, we materialize the results of the
4470 MATCH functions before they are seen by AggregateIterator.
4471
4472 The most important thing to materialize is the MATCH function, but
4473 AggregateIterator is not currently prepared for reading some data from a
4474 materialized source and other data directly from the base tables, so we have
4475 to materialize all expressions that are to be used as input to
4476 AggregateIterator.
4477
4478 The old optimizer does not have special code for materializing MATCH
4479 functions. In most cases it does not need it, because it usually performs
4480 aggregation by materializing all expressions (not only MATCH) in the SELECT
4481 list, the GROUP BY clause and the ORDER BY clause anyway. It does not,
4482 however, materialize the non-aggregated expressions in the HAVING clause, so
4483 calls to the MATCH function in the HAVING clause may give wrong results with
4484 the old optimizer.
4485
4486 The old optimizer uses the same sort-based aggregation as the hypergraph
4487 optimizer for ROLLUP. The lack of materialization of MATCH expressions leads
4488 to wrong results also when MATCH is used in the SELECT list or the ORDER BY
4489 clause of a ROLLUP query.
4490
4491 The materialization performed by this function makes the hypergraph optimizer
4492 produce correct results for the above mentioned cases where the old optimizer
4493 produces wrong results.
4494 */

4500 // materialize every sub-expression if a non-leaf item can be materialized.
4501 // We don't use the transformation capability of CompileItem, hence the
4502 // transformer argument is a simple identity function.
4503
1/2
✓ Branch 0 taken 22 times.
✗ Branch 1 not taken.

4776 // Checks if an item represents a full-text predicate which can be satisfied by
4777 // a full-text index scan. This can be done if the predicate is on one of the
4778 // following forms:
4779 //
4780 // MATCH(col) AGAINST ('search string')
4781 // MATCH(col) AGAINST ('search string') > const, where const >= 0
4782 // MATCH(col) AGAINST ('search string') >= const, where const > 0
4783 // const < MATCH(col) AGAINST ('search string'), where const >= 0
4784 // const <= MATCH(col) AGAINST ('search string'), where const > 0
4785 //
4786 // That is, the predicate must return FALSE if MATCH returns zero. The predicate
4787 // cannot be pushed to an index scan if it returns TRUE when MATCH returns zero,

5078 // If we have both ORDER BY and GROUP BY, we need a materialization step
5079 // after the grouping (if windowing hasn't already given us one) -- although
5080 // in most cases, we only need to materialize one row at a time (streaming),
5081 // so the performance loss should be very slight. This is because when
5082 // filesort only really deals with fields, not values; when it is to “output”
5083 // a row, it puts back the contents of the sorted table's (or tables')
5084 // row buffer(s). For expressions that only depend on the current row, such as
5085 // (f1 + 1), this is fine, but aggregate functions (Item_sum) depend on
5086 // multiple rows, so we need a field where filesort can put back its value
5087 // (and of course, subsequent readers need to read from that field
5088 // instead of trying to evaluate the Item_sum). A temporary table provides
5089 // just that, so we create one based on the current field list;
5090 // StreamingIterator (or MaterializeIterator, if we actually need to
5091 // materialize) will evaluate all the Items in turn and put their values
5092 // into the temporary table's fields.
5093 //
5094 // For simplicity, we materialize all items in the SELECT list, even those
5095 // that are not aggregate functions. This is a tiny performance loss,
5096 // but makes things simpler.

5305
5306 /**
5307 Find the ordering that allows us to process the most unprocessed windows.
5308 If specified, we can also demand that the ordering satisfies one or two
5309 later orderings (for DISTINCT and/or ORDER BY).
5310
5311 Our priorities are, in strict order:
5312
5313 1. Satisfying both DISTINCT and ORDER BY (if both are given;
5314 but see below).
5315 2. Satisfying the first operation after windowing
5316 (which is either DISTINCT or ORDER BY).
5317 3. Satisfying as many windows as possible.
5318 4. The shortest possible ordering (as a tie-breaker).
5319
5320 If first_ordering_idx is given, #2 is mandatory. #4 is so that we don't
5321 get strange situations where the user specifies e.g. OVER (ORDER BY i)
5322 and we choose an ordering i,j,k,l,... because it happened to be given
5323 somewhere else.
5324
5325 Note that normally, it is very hard to satisfy DISTINCT for a window
5326 function, because generally, it isn't constant for a given input
5327 (by nature, it also depends on other rows). But it can happen if the
5328 window frame is static; see main.window_functions_interesting_orders.
5329
5330 @param join Contains the list of windows.
5331 @param orderings Logical orderings in the query block.
5332 @param sort_ahead_orderings Candidate orderings to consider.
5333 @param fd_set Active functional dependencies.
5334 @param finished_windows Windows to ignore.
5335 @param tmp_buffer Temporary space for keeping the best list
5336 of windows so far; must be as large as
5337 the number of values.
5338 @param first_ordering_idx The first ordering after the query block
5339 that we need to satisfy (-1 if none).
5340 @param second_ordering_idx The second ordering after the query block
5341 that we would like to satisfy (-1 if none).
5342 @param [out] included_windows Which windows can be sorted using the given
5343 ordering.
5344
5345 @return An index into sort_ahead_orderings, or -1 if no ordering could
5346 be found that sorts at least one window (plus, if first_ordering_idx
5347 is set, follows that ordering).
5348 */
5349 19 static int FindBestOrderingForWindow(
5350 JOIN *join, const LogicalOrderings &orderings,
5351 FunctionalDependencySet fd_set,
5352 const Mem_root_array<SortAheadOrdering> &sort_ahead_orderings,
5353 Bounds_checked_array<bool> finished_windows,
5354 Bounds_checked_array<bool> tmp_buffer, int first_ordering_idx,
5355 int second_ordering_idx, Bounds_checked_array<bool> included_windows) {

5467 /**
5468 Apply window functions.
5469
5470 Ordering of window functions is a tricky topic. We can apply window functions
5471 in any order that we'd like, but we would like to do as few sorts as possible.
5472 In its most general form, this would entail solving an instance of the
5473 traveling salesman problem (TSP), and although the number of windows is
5474 typically small (one or two in most queries), this can blow up for large
5475 numbers of windows.
5476
5477 Thankfully, window functions never add or remove rows. We also assume that all
5478 sorts are equally expensive (which isn't really true, as ones on more columns
5479 take more processing time and buffer, but it's close enough in practice),
5480 and we also ignore the fact that as we compute more buffers, the temporary
5481 tables and sort buffers will get more columns. These assumptions, combined
5482 with some reasonable assumptions about ordering transitivity (if an ordering A
5483 is more sorted than an ordering B, and B > C, then also A > C -- the only
5484 thing that can disturb this is groupings, which we ignore for the sake of
5485 simplicity), mean that we need to care _only_ about the number of sorts, and
5486 can do them greedily. Thus, at any point, we pick the ordering that allows us
5487 to process the largest number of windows, process them, remove them from
5488 consideration, and repeat until there are none left.
5489
5490 There is one more ordering complication; after windowing, we may have DISTINCT
5491 and/or ORDER BY, which may also benefit from groupings/orderings we leave
5492 after the last window. Thus, first of all, we see if there's an ordering that
5493 can satisfy them (ideally both if possible) _and_ at least one window; if so,
5494 we save that ordering and those windows for last.
5495
5496 Temporary tables are set up in FinalizePlanForQueryBlock(). This is so that
5497 it is easier to have multiple different orderings for the temporary table
5498 parameters later.
5499 */
5500 27 static Prealloced_array<AccessPath *, 4> ApplyWindowFunctions(

5817 /**
5818 Find the lowest-cost plan (which hopefully is also the cheapest to execute)
5819 of all the legal ways to execute the query. The overall order of operations is
5820 largely dictated by the standard:
5821
5822 1. All joined tables, including join predicates.
5823 2. WHERE predicates (we push these down into #1 where allowed)
5824 3. GROUP BY (it is sometimes possible to push this down into #1,
5825 but we don't have the functionality to do so).
5826 4. HAVING.
5827 5. Window functions.
5828 6. DISTINCT.
5829 7. ORDER BY.
5830 8. LIMIT.
5831 9. SQL_BUFFER_RESULT (a MySQL extension).
5832
5833 The place where we have the most leeway by far is #1, which is why this
5834 part of the optimizer is generally called the join optimizer (there are
5835 potentially billions of different join orderings, whereas each of the
5836 other steps, except windowing, can only be done in one or two ways).
5837 But the various outputs of #1 can have different properties, that can make
5838 for higher or lower costs in the other steps. (For instance, LIMIT will
5839 affect candidates with different init_cost differently, and ordering
5840 properties can skip sorting in ORDER BY entirely.) Thus, we allow keeping
5841 multiple candidates in play at every step if they are meaningfully different,
5842 and only pick out the winning candidate based on cost at the very end.
5843 */
5844 239 AccessPath *FindBestQueryPlan(THD *thd, Query_block *query_block,
